<div class="comments-head">Comments: In defense of PDF ...</div>


<div class="comments-body">
<p>I appreciate your list of reasons for adopting PDF for your newsletter.  While I'm not a big fan of PDFs, I do like their self-contained nature.  However, I don't consider it a good way to handle longer blogs, as it seems to defeat the nature of the blogging medium.</p>

<p>However, your reasoning caused me to recall a web news site whose format I've always enjoyed and that adheres to many of your ideals - the International Herald Tribune - and thought you might want to take a look.  Here's a representative piece:</p>

<p>http://www.iht.com/articles/114576.html</p>

<p>Via the "toolbar" at bottom, they provide formatting alternatives - one column/one page or multi-columns/multi-pages (my preference), as well as options to increase/decrease the font size, and a nice print layout option.  They deliver the entire article to you, so no round-trips are required, even when displayed in multi-page mode.  If the graphics were eliminated and the javascript embedded, it could be read off-line.  One thing that's bothersome is having to use the mouse to click between pages (although they mitigated this some by allowing you to click anywhere near the ending/beginning of the article text).</p>

<p>I suppose in the end, good content trumps format anyway.  </p>

<p>Good luck with the newsletter.<br />
</p>
<span class="comments-post">Posted by <a target="_blank" href="http://ewbi.blogs.com/develops/">Eric W. Bachtal</a> at October 21, 2003 02:13 PM</span>
</div>
